Reasoning: The paper discusses the use of artificial neural networks (ANNs) for vision problems, specifically deep convolutional networks. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel efficient network pruning method, which involves removing network parameters or filter channels based on a criterion and a schedule. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of a L0 constraint instead of the L1 penalty, which may suggest that it belongs to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves experimental validation on synthetic and real datasets, which may suggest that it belongs to the data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category.
